  keywords = {TRPV1, vascular smooth muscle, vasoconstriction, blood pressure, arteriole, lysophosphatidic acid, inflammatory lipids},
  certainty = {0.72},
  research_stream = {trp-pentamer-vascular},
  note     = {Pharmacological antagonism + genetic knockout. TRPV1 localizes to terminal arterioles throughout circulation (skeletal muscle, heart, adipose). Capsaicin causes dose-dependent vasoconstriction and elevated systemic blood pressure; effect persists after sensory nerve ablation (confirming vascular-intrinsic, not neuronal). Arteriolar TRPV1 resistant to activity-induced desensitization (unlike sensory neurons). Lysophosphatidic acid (endogenous inflammatory lipid) activates arteriolar TRPV1. Mechanistically: depolarizing current -> L-type Ca2+ channel activation -> sustained vasoconstriction. Relevant to PEM hypothesis: inflammatory lipids during exercise-induced tissue damage could activate arteriolar TRPV1 causing inappropriate sustained vasoconstriction.}
}

