  doi      = {10.1001/archpsyc.63.11.1267},
  pmid     = {17088507},
  url      = {https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17088507/},
  keywords = {chronic fatigue, premorbid, stress, emotional instability, twin study, Swedish Twin Registry, prospective, predictors, genetics, environment},
  certainty = {0.50},
  research_stream = {lower-baseline-predisposition},
  note     = {Prospective nested case-control in Swedish Twin Registry. N=19,192 twins; pre-illness measures taken 25 years before fatigue onset. Emotional instability: 55--72\% increased risk in initial analyses, but effect disappeared in discordant MZ pairs, indicating genetic basis. Perceived stress: 64--65\% elevated risk; strengthened to 5.81-fold after genetic control, indicating true environmental causal factor. Extraversion: no association. LIMITATION: outcome is ``chronic fatigue'' broadly defined, not strictly ME/CFS; predictors are psychological instruments not physiological biomarkers; 25-year lead time may miss onset-proximate prodromal factors. CAUTION: emotional instability as premorbid predictor may partly reflect subclinical autonomic dysregulation mislabeled as personality trait.}
